A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in the 'uncultivated' HIV virus
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds capable of moderateing the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, such as some accessible medicines already.
AIDS cannot be cured until now.
However, the life of patients can be significantly prolonged by a combination of medicines that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely eliminated, the so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the medicines will no longer work.
The work of the experts from the three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg shows the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that substances called metalocarbons have an effect on the albumin, responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metalcarbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way than all the medicines used today, so they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists find new, ‘improved’ compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the virus albumin.
The metalocarbons have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyedron cells composed of the atoms of boron, hydrogen and carbon are bound by the atom of metal, in this case by cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and it is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, there is no HIV fractionation and no mature and infectious body cells of the virus would be created.
