A United Nations group is drawing up a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, which has so far been characterized by challenging positions and mutual recriminations, renewed focus on Friday with the release of a document that provides for ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important advance in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Drafted by an ad hoc working group of the United Nations, the text does not say how much money the rich countries would give to the poor to cope with global short- and long-term warming.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their carbon production, and what would be the limit of the global increase in the temperature that political strategies would be willing to tolerate.
This gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequiyt, High Representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate officer, Yvo de Boer, described as "the great panorama."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by between 25 and 45 per cent by 2020, compared with 1990 levels, while the main developing countries would reduce their emissions during the same period between 15 and 30 per cent.
Together, countries would cut emissions from 50 to 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union also stimulated talks Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and drought to deforestation.
Anyway, Friday presented the same kind of verbal artificial fires that dominated the conversations last week.
The United States Special Climate Envoy Todd Stern rejected claims that require mandatory greenhouse gas emissions cuts for industrialized countries, compared with those of the major emerging economies, if they were not financed by the developed world.
