Management revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of the great French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with regard to their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is that employees adhere to "values" determined from above as it was earlier to impose on consumers products thought of by factory technicians.
By putting the customer in the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to market conquest strategies... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that do not relate to customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
Demobilization of employees can end in mortal demortification.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the company's intellectual functions, especially R+D and, more importantly, business intelligence.
Indeed, the IB (Business Intelligence) "requires all parties involved (...) to have proactive conduct and perspective" ; it requires employees to make a commitment that completely opposes the recommendations of an authority.
For this reason, we call for a managerial revolution, which would consist of putting employees at the centre of the company's concerns as much as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as Orange's questionnaire among employees, encourage the management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I could verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many rounds, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
- Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most of the directors have a simple view of human behavior.
As they come from large engineering schools, they interpret psychology mechanically.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the former behaviorist theory that the American "neurosciences" recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media have widely spread to their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of the commitment of the executives, a recent investigation of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the directors in a mechanicalist management position, not adapted to today's world.
Identify and measure the mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution needed for the good functioning of modern companies is to adopt a final view of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into any reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means of making reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the Motivational Analysis adopt this concept of employee motivation.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a default dock that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of the mobilization factors, business managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and replace the management of human resources "in place".
In this way, they create a favourable ground for organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
