The dynasium cunae
The Tawa Findae had the same look as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal two meters long and 150 meters high that ran on the two strong legs behind, had an enlarged head with sharp teeth and curves, short arms with wooden hooks and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would not have been something special.
But Tawa foundae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry area of the Pangea supercontinent in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us much about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists launched an excavation in 2006 in Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes, we have found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, this is something unprecedented for Triásico sediments, reports Randall Irmis member of the Utah Natural History Museum team.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation, the remaining five specimens gathered together.
A finding confirms the theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional finding: "The triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share such enthusiasm at all.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, comments Martin Sander of the University of Bonn, for example.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these first dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts discuss, for example, when the Saurios were divided into their three most important genealogical lines: the carnivorous teropodes among which are the Tyronasaurus Rex, Velociroptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the Ornithichia herbivoros (sauri with avian pelvis), to which they belong, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to Nesbitt's analysis and his colleagues, Tawa Findae is a primitive thermopod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in the Tawa skull the researchers found signs of air bags, such as those that also possess the descendants of the teropodes, the birds.
Thanks to the airbags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa also found the bones of the spine were obviously partially air-filled.
Tawa is the older and primitive air bags teropode, says Randall Irmis.
Because the parent line of the later giant sauropods also had air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far lived in South America, researchers have concluded that the Saurios first emerged there.
Thus, the three genealogical lines separated from South America at the beginning and extended from South America through all the corners of the Earth, which was then still forming a single earth mass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say that the team found together with Tawa found the remains of two other teropodes not very closely related.
The three cannot come down from a single parenting predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe that there have been at least three migratory waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a group of dinosaurs, lived in the present Poland, notes paleontologist Bonn Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted picture, because in South America many dinosaur fossils are still being preserved, while in other continents there is only something to discover.
The question of how the evolutionary dinosaurs of a relatively rare sideline of reptiles to the dominant earthly vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
In the Triásico, dinosaurs still shared their vital space with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of the current crocodiles and the pterosaurs and many others.
Towards the end of the Triásico, dinosaurs spread throughout the world and many new species developed, while the relative was extinct at the border of the Triásico towards the Jurásico.
Success stories were not eternal
There are two possibilities to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a massive extinction to which dinosaurs by chance survived, but the other reptiles did not.
Or dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Success stories aren't always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact slows the growth of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triaic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
